  "prompt": "Which one is grammatically correct: pick up someone at the airport or from the airport?",
  "response": "Both \"pick up someone at the airport\" and \"pick up someone from the airport\" are grammatically correct, but they have slightly different connotations.\n\n- \"Pick up someone at the airport\" suggests that you are going to the airport to meet someone and collect them from there.\n- \"Pick up someone from the airport\" also means that you are taking someone from the airport, but it emphasizes the origin more (i.e., you're picking someone up and taking them away from the airport).\n\nIn most contexts, the difference is subtle, and either version would be understood correctly. It's largely a matter of personal preference or regional variation.",
